'''John Vincent Beckett''', [[Fellow of the Society Antiquaries|FSA]], [[Fellow of the Royal Historical Society|FRHistS]] (born 12 July 1950) is an English local historian who has been Professor of English Regional History at the [[University of Nottingham]] since 1990.
== Career and research == Beckett was born on 12 July 1950 to William Vincent Beckett and his wife, Kathleen Amelia, ''née'' Reed. He completed an undergraduate degree at the [[University of Lancaster]] in 1971, which awarded him a [[doctor of philosophy]] degree four years later for his thesis "Land ownership in Cumbria, c. 1680–c. 1750".<ref name=":0">[http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-70887 "Beckett, Prof. John Vincent"], ''[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]'' (online edition, Oxford University Press, December 2017). Retrieved 8 May 2018.</ref><ref>[http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?did=1&uin=uk.bl.ethos.449351 "Landownership in Cumbria c.1680-c.1750"], ''EthOS'' ([[British Library]]). Retrieved 8 May 2018.</ref>
From 1974 to 1976, Beckett was the Lord Adams Research Fellow at [[Newcastle University]]; he then spent two years lecturing at [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]]'s [[Banbury]]-based Wroxton College, and then lectured at the [[University of Hull]] for a short period before taking up a lectureship at the [[University of Nottingham]] in 1979. He was promoted to a readership in English regional history in 1987, and three years later promoted to his current professorship. Beckett was also Director of the [[Victoria County History]] series from 2005 to 2010, and has served as chairman of a number of editorial boards, including that of the journal ''[[Midlands History]]'' (since 2001) and the History of Lincolnshire Committee of the [[Society for Lincolnshire History and Archaeology]] (since 1988). He has been chairman of the [[Thoroton Society]] since 1992 and chaired the [[British Agricultural History Society]] for four years from 2001.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" />
Becket is a historian of England in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. He is a [[English local history|local historian]], and has studied topics relating to village life, [[Inclosure Acts|Parliamentary enclosure]] and local politics, agricultural history, church history, and the history of [[landed estate]]s and their owners.<ref name=":1">{{cite web|url=https://www.nottingham.ac.uk/humanities/departments/history/people/john.beckett|title=John Beckett|last=|first=|date=|website=University of Nottingham|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=8 May 2018}}</ref>
=== Honours === Beckett was elected a [[Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries of London]] in 1992,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sal.org.uk/about-us/fellows-directory/B/page/5/|title=Fellows Directory - Society of Antiquaries|website=Sal.org.uk|accessdate=1 December 2017}}</ref> and is also a [[Fellow of the Royal Historical Society]] as of 2018.<ref>[https://5hm1h4aktue2uejbs1hsqt31-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/RHS-Fellows-B.pdf "Fellows – B"], ''Royal Historical Society''. Retrieved 8 May 2018.</ref>
==Selected publications== * ''Coal and Tobacco: The Lowthers and the Economic Development of West Cumberland 1660–1760'' (Cambridge University Press, 1981). * ''The Aristocracy in England, 1660–1914'' (Blackwell, 1986). * ''The East Midlands from AD 1000'' (Longman, 1988). * ''A History of Laxton: England’s Last Open-Field Village'' (Blackwell, 1989). * ''The Agricultural Revolution'' (Blackwell, 1990). * ''Rise and Fall of the Grenvilles: Dukes of Buckingham and Chandos, 1710 to 1921'' (Manchester University Press, 1994). * (Co-editor with [[Michael Turner (historian)|Michael Turner]] and Bethanie Afton) ''Agricultural Rent in England 1690–1914'' (Cambridge University Press, 1997). * (Editor) ''A Centenary History of Nottingham'' (Manchester University Press, 1997). * (Co-editor with [[Michael Turner (historian)|Michael Turner]] and Bethanie Afton) ''Farm Production in England 1700–1914'' (Cambridge University Press, 2001). * ''Byron and Newstead: The Aristocrat and the Abbey'' (University of Delaware Press, 2001). * ''Nottinghamshire Past: Essays in Honour of [[Adrian Henstock]]'' (Merton Priority Press for Nottinghamshire County Council, 2003). * ''City Status in the British Isles, 1830–2002'' (Ashgate, 2005). * ''Writing Local History'' (Manchester University Press, 2007). * ''Nottingham: A History of Britain's Global University'' (Boydell Press, 2016).
